{% title "The relationship between determinants and area or volume" "Overview" %}
{% description "The properties of the cross product and the scalar triple product give links between determinants and area or volume. " %}

<p>From the properties of the {%intlink cross_product %}geometric definition of the cross product{%endintlink%} and the {%intlink scalar_triple_product%}scalar triple product{%endintlink%}, we can discover a link between $2 \times 2$ determinants and area, and a link between $3 \times 3$ determinants and volume.</p>

{% index_entry "area" "parallelogram" "area2d" %}{% index_entry "parallelogram" "area"  "area2d1" %}{% navigation_tag "area2d2" "Area" %}
<h4>2 $\times$ 2 determinants and area</h4>

<p>{%intlink cross_product %}The area of the parallelogram{%endintlink%}
spanned by $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{b}$ is the magnitude of
$\vc{a} \times \vc{b}$.  We can write the cross product of $\vc{a} =
a_1\vc{i}+a_2\vc{j}+a_3\vc{k}$ and $\vc{b} =
b_1\vc{i}+b_2\vc{j}+b_3\vc{k}$ as the determinant
\begin{align*}
\vc{a} \times \vc{b}=  \left|
      \begin{array}{ccc}
        \vc{i} &amp; \vc{j} &amp; \vc{k}\\
        a_1 &amp; a_2 &amp; a_3\\
        b_1 &amp; b_2 &amp; b_3
      \end{array}
    \right|.
\end{align*}
</p>

<p>Now, imagine that $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{b}$ lie in the plane so that $a_3
= b_3=0$.  Using the {%intlink matrices_determinants_multivariable_calculus %}rules for calculating determinants{%endintlink%}, we see that, in this case,
the cross product simplifies to
\begin{align*}
\vc{a} \times \vc{b}=  \left|
      \begin{array}{cc}
        a_1 &amp; a_2\\
        b_1 &amp; b_2
      \end{array}
    \right|
    \vc{k}.
\end{align*}
</p>

<p>
Hence, the area of the parallelogram, $\| \vc{a} \times \vc{b}\|$, is
the absolute value of the determinant
\begin{align*}
  \left|
    \begin{array}{cc}
      a_1 &amp; a_2\\
      b_1 &amp; b_2
    \end{array}
  \right|.
\end{align*}
As mentioned in the discussion about 
{%intlink matrices_determinants_multivariable_calculus altnotation%}determinant notation{%endintlink%}, 
it's difficult to
represent the absolute value of a determinant using the above notation.
Instead, we write that the area of the parallelogram spanned by
$\vc{a} = a_1 \vc{i} + a_2 \vc{j}$ and $\vc{b} = b_1 \vc{i} +
b_2\vc{j}$ is
\begin{align*}
  \| \vc{a} \times \vc{b}\| 
  =\left|\det \left(\left[
      \begin{array}{cc}
        a_1 &amp; a_2\\
        b_1 &amp; b_2
      \end{array}
    \right]\right)
 \right|.
\end{align*}
</p>


{% index_entry "volume" "parallelepiped" "volume3d" %}{% index_entry "parallelepiped" "volume" "volume3d1" %}{% navigation_tag "volume3d2" "Volume" %}
<h4>3 $\times$ 3 determinants and volume</h4>

<p>The {%intlink scalar_triple_product%}volume of a parallelepiped{%endintlink%}
spanned by the vectors
$\vc{a}$, $\vc{b}$ and $\vc{c}$ is the absolute value of the
{%intlink scalar_triple_product%}scalar triple product{%endintlink%}
$(\vc{a} \times \vc{b}) \cdot \vc{c}$.  We can write the scalar triple
product of $\vc{a} = a_1\vc{i}+a_2\vc{j}+a_3\vc{k}$, $\vc{b} =
b_1\vc{i}+b_2\vc{j}+b_3\vc{k}$, and $\vc{c} =
c_1\vc{i}+c_2\vc{j}+c_3\vc{k}$ as the determinant
\begin{align*}
  (\vc{a} \times \vc{b}) \cdot \vc{c}
  =
  \left|
    \begin{array}{ccc}
      a_1 &amp; a_2 &amp; a_3\\
      b_1 &amp; b_2 &amp; b_3\\
      c_1 &amp; c_2 &amp; c_3
    \end{array}
  \right|.
\end{align*}
Hence, using the {%intlink matrices_determinants_multivariable_calculus altnotation%}alternative notation for determinant{%endintlink%}, the volume of the parallelepiped spanned by $\vc{a}$, $\vc{b}$,
and $\vc{c}$ is
\begin{align*}
  |(\vc{a} \times \vc{b}) \cdot \vc{c}|
  =
\left|\det \left(\left[
    \begin{array}{ccc}
      a_1 &amp; a_2 &amp; a_3\\
      b_1 &amp; b_2 &amp; b_3\\
      c_1 &amp; c_2 &amp; c_3
    \end{array}
   \right]\right)
 \right|.
\end{align*}
</p>

